## 1. Introduction

### 1.1 Scope

This ticket implements three code quality/analysis features:

1. **Find Duplicates** — Detect near-duplicate code using embedding similarity (not just text matching)
2. **Dead Code Detection** — Identify unreachable/unused code with confidence scoring
3. **Git History Mining** — Semantic search over git commit history (messages + diffs)

These features leverage the full-body embedding (KSA-169), call graph (KSA-154), and AST infrastructure (KSA-145).

### 1.2 Out of Scope

* Auto-refactoring of duplicates (only detection)
* Cross-repository duplicate detection
* Git blame integration (line-level attribution)
* Code coverage integration (runtime dead code)
* Git bisect automation

### 1.3 Preliminary Requirements

* KSA-169: Full-body Embedding (for semantic duplicate detection)
* KSA-145: Tree-sitter Core (AST parsing)
* KSA-154: Call Graph (for dead code — reachability analysis)
* Git repository with history (for git mining)

## 2. Business Requirements

### 2.1 High Level Process Map

These three features address code quality from different angles: - Duplicates: reduce maintenance burden by finding copy-paste code - Dead code: reduce codebase size by finding unused code - Git mining: find historical context for code decisions

### 2.2 List of User Stories / Use Cases

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | Story / Use Case | Priority | Source Ticket |
| 1 | As a developer, I want near-duplicate code detected so that I can refactor shared logic | MUST HAVE | KSA-168 |
| 2 | As a developer, I want dead code identified so that I can safely remove unused code | MUST HAVE | KSA-168 |
| 3 | As a developer, I want to search git history semantically so that I can find why code was written | SHOULD HAVE | KSA-168 |
| 4 | As a developer, I want confidence scores on dead code so that I don’t accidentally remove used code | MUST HAVE | KSA-168 |
| 5 | As a developer, I want duplicate clusters grouped so that I can see all copies at once | SHOULD HAVE | KSA-168 |

### 2.3 Details of User Stories

#### Business Flow

**Step 1:** System indexes all function bodies with full-body embeddings (KSA-169)

**Step 2:** For duplicate detection: compute pairwise cosine similarity between embeddings

**Step 3:** Group functions with similarity > threshold (default 0.85) into clusters

**Step 4:** For dead code: build reachability graph from entry points (KSA-154 call graph)

**Step 5:** Functions not reachable from any entry point = potentially dead

**Step 6:** Apply confidence scoring (export usage, test references, dynamic dispatch)

**Step 7:** For git mining: index commit messages + diff summaries with embeddings

**Step 8:** Semantic search over git history returns relevant commits

#### STORY 1: Find Duplicates (Embedding-based)

As a developer, I want near-duplicate code detected so that I can refactor shared logic.

**Requirement Details:**

**Detection Approach:** 1. Use full-body embeddings (from KSA-169) for each function 2. Compute cosine similarity between all function pairs 3. Threshold: similarity > 0.85 = near-duplicate (configurable) 4. Group duplicates into clusters (transitive closure) 5. Report: cluster members, similarity scores, diff highlights

**Similarity Levels:**

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Level | Threshold | Meaning |
| Exact | > 0.99 | Identical logic (possibly different variable names) |
| Near-duplicate | > 0.90 | Same algorithm, minor differences |
| Similar | > 0.85 | Similar approach, some structural differences |
| Related | > 0.75 | Related logic, worth reviewing |

**MCP Tool: find\_duplicates**

Input: - file\_path (optional): Scope to specific file - min\_similarity (optional): Minimum similarity threshold (default: 0.85) - min\_lines (optional): Minimum function size to consider (default: 5 lines) - cross\_file (optional): Search across files (default: true)

Output:

{
 "clusters": [
 {
 "id": "DUP-001",
 "members": [
 {"file": "src/utils/sort.py", "function": "quicksort", "lines": [10, 45], "similarity": 1.0},
 {"file": "src/legacy/sorting.py", "function": "fast\_sort", "lines": [22, 58], "similarity": 0.94}
 ],
 "avg\_similarity": 0.94,
 "suggestion": "Extract shared sorting logic into common module"
 }
 ],
 "summary": {"total\_clusters": 5, "total\_duplicates": 12, "lines\_duplicated": 340}
}

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Detects semantically similar functions (not just text-identical)
2. Finds duplicates across different files
3. Groups duplicates into clusters
4. Configurable similarity threshold
5. Minimum 5-line functions (skip trivial getters/setters)
6. Performance: < 30s for 1000-function codebase

#### STORY 2: Dead Code Detection

As a developer, I want dead code identified so that I can safely remove unused code.

**Requirement Details:**

**Detection Approach:** 1. Build reachability graph from entry points (main, HTTP handlers, exports, CLI commands) 2. Functions NOT reachable from any entry point = potentially dead 3. Apply confidence scoring to reduce false positives

**Confidence Scoring:**

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Factor | Impact on Confidence | Example |
| No callers in call graph | +40% dead | Function never called |
| Not exported/public | +20% dead | Private function |
| No test references | +15% dead | Not tested either |
| Has TODO/deprecated comment | +15% dead | Marked for removal |
| Used via reflection/dynamic dispatch | -30% dead | May be called dynamically |
| Referenced in config/DI | -20% dead | Dependency injection |
| Recently modified (< 30 days) | -10% dead | Active development |

**Confidence Levels:**

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Score | Level | Recommendation |
| >= 80% | High | Safe to remove |
| 60-79% | Medium | Review before removing |
| 40-59% | Low | Likely used dynamically |
| < 40% | Very Low | Probably not dead |

**MCP Tool: find\_dead\_code**

Input: - file\_path (optional): Scope to specific file - min\_confidence (optional): Minimum confidence (default: 60%) - include\_tests (optional): Include test-only code (default: false)

Output:

{
 "dead\_code": [
 {
 "file": "src/legacy/old\_parser.py",
 "function": "parse\_v1",
 "lines": [10, 85],
 "confidence": 92,
 "reasons": ["no\_callers", "not\_exported", "no\_tests", "has\_deprecated\_comment"],
 "last\_modified": "2024-01-15"
 }
 ],
 "summary": {"total\_dead": 15, "total\_lines": 450, "high\_confidence": 8, "medium\_confidence": 7}
}

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Identifies functions with no callers in call graph
2. Confidence scoring reduces false positives
3. Respects dynamic dispatch patterns (reflection, DI)
4. Reports last modification date for context
5. Does NOT flag entry points, exports, or test utilities
6. Performance: < 20s for 1000-function codebase

#### STORY 3: Git History Mining

As a developer, I want to search git history semantically so that I can find why code was written.

**Requirement Details:**

**Indexing:** 1. Parse git log: commit hash, author, date, message, files changed 2. For each commit: generate embedding of (message + file list + diff summary) 3. Store in vector index for semantic search 4. Incremental: only index new commits since last run

**Search Capabilities:** - Natural language query: “when was authentication added” - File-specific: “changes to database.py related to connection pooling” - Author-specific: “commits by John about performance” - Time-range: “changes in last 3 months about security”

**MCP Tool: mine\_git\_history**

Input: - query (required): Natural language search query - file\_path (optional): Filter to specific file - author (optional): Filter by author - since (optional): Date filter (ISO format) - limit (optional): Max results (default: 10)

Output:

{
 "commits": [
 {
 "hash": "abc123",
 "author": "John Doe",
 "date": "2025-03-15",
 "message": "Add connection pooling to database module",
 "files\_changed": ["src/db/pool.py", "src/db/connection.py"],
 "relevance\_score": 0.92
 }
 ]
}

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Indexes git commit messages and diff summaries
2. Semantic search finds relevant commits by meaning (not just keyword)
3. File-specific search narrows to commits touching that file
4. Incremental indexing (only new commits)
5. Performance: search < 500ms, indexing < 60s for 10K commits

#### STORY 4: Confidence Scoring for Dead Code

As a developer, I want confidence scores on dead code so that I don’t accidentally remove used code.

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Every dead code finding has a confidence score (0-100%)
2. Score factors are transparent (listed in output)
3. Dynamic dispatch patterns reduce confidence appropriately
4. Recently modified code gets lower dead-code confidence
5. Configurable minimum confidence threshold

#### STORY 5: Duplicate Clusters

As a developer, I want duplicate clusters grouped so that I can see all copies at once.

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Duplicates grouped by transitive similarity
2. Cluster shows all members with pairwise similarity
3. Largest/oldest member suggested as “canonical” version
4. Diff between cluster members available on request

