## 5. Risks and Assumptions

### 5.1 Risks

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Risk | Impact | Likelihood | Mitigation |
| Dead code false positives (dynamic dispatch) | High | High | Confidence scoring, conservative defaults |
| Duplicate detection too sensitive (trivial matches) | Medium | Medium | Minimum line threshold, configurable similarity |
| Git history too large to index (100K+ commits) | Medium | Medium | Incremental indexing, time-range limits |
| Embedding similarity doesn’t capture structural differences | Medium | Medium | Combine with AST-based structural comparison |

### 5.2 Assumptions

* Full-body embeddings (KSA-169) provide meaningful similarity scores
* Call graph (KSA-154) is complete enough for reachability analysis
* Git commit messages are descriptive enough for semantic search
* Cosine similarity > 0.85 reliably indicates near-duplicate code
* Entry point detection covers all reachability roots

## 6. Non-Functional Requirements

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Category | Requirement | Details |
| Performance | Duplicate scan < 30s | 1000-function codebase |
| Performance | Dead code scan < 20s | 1000-function codebase |
| Performance | Git search < 500ms | Query response time |
| Performance | Git indexing < 60s | 10K commits |
| Accuracy | Dead code FP < 20% | With confidence >= 80% |
| Accuracy | Duplicate precision >= 90% | At threshold 0.85 |

